{"action_ids":["17","24","25"],"summary":"Evidence regarding the impact of organic farming on wild bees is inconsistent. Three replicated trials in Europe or Canada have indicated a higher abundance and, in one case, greater diversity of wild bees under organic arable farming compared to conventional methods (25). However, three other replicated trials in Europe or the USA found no significant differences in the numbers of bumblebees, bumblebee species, or wild bees visiting flowering crops between conventional and organic farms (25).

Agri-environment schemes have also shown mixed results. Four replicated trials in Europe demonstrated enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land managed under such schemes (24). Conversely, four other replicated trials in Europe found no enhancement in the number of bees or bee species on land managed under similar schemes, and two UK trials found no enhancement of bumblebee populations on a wider landscape scale (24).

Planting dedicated floral resources on farmland has been shown to attract wild bees. Fourteen trials in Europe and North America recorded substantial numbers of wild bees foraging on sown flowering plants (17). Specifically, ten trials found that patches of Phacelia tanacetifolia attracted considerable numbers of foraging wild bees, particularly bumblebees (17), although one trial in Greece noted it was not very attractive to wild bees (17). Additionally, a UK trial found that perennial leguminous herbs like clovers were more appealing to bumblebees in landscapes with a higher proportion of arable farming (17). While these plantings attract foraging bees, evidence for a wider population benefit is mixed. One trial showed that planting lupine in orchards enhanced the reproductive success of blue orchard mason bees (17), but another trial found no increase in bee numbers or species richness in farmland 50-1,500m away from flower patches (17), and two other trials found few solitary bees nesting in fields sown with phacelia or clover (17).","query":"Beyond simply reducing general pesticide use on agricultural land, what other farming system changes show potential benefits for wild bees?"}

